{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LxUZTRosPnFwXgnzUCqxf9","type":"tool_result","content":"  4300→* **Test strategy**\n  4301→\n  4302→  * state-machine tests\n  4303→  * cache tests\n  4304→  * conformance scenarios\n  4305→\n  4306→* **Migration strategy**\n  4307→\n  4308→  * none; new command surface only\n  4309→\n  4310→* **Rollback or safety considerations**\n  4311→\n  4312→  * validated requirements required before project handoff\n  4313→\n  4314→* **Risks**\n  4315→\n  4316→  * requirements and delivery workflows becoming too tightly coupled\n  4317→\n  4318→## Slice 11: Automation Runtime\n  4319→\n  4320→* **Slice name**\n  4321→  Daemon, routing, worktrees, and issue automation\n  4322→\n  4323→* **Bounded context**\n  4324→  Automation Runtime\n  4325→\n  4326→* **Why it exists**\n  4327→  It depends on most other contracts and should come late.\n  4328→\n  4329→* **Goal**\n  4330→\n  4331→  * implement daemon lifecycle\n  4332→  * implement label and explicit command routing\n  4333→  * implement worktree leases\n  4334→  * dispatch workflow or requirements tasks\n  4335→  * implement draft PR watcher and rebase\n  4336→  * implement interactive requirements issue path\n  4337→\n  4338→* **Prerequisites**\n  4339→\n  4340→  * Slices 3-10\n  4341→\n  4342→* **Exact scope**\n  4343→\n  4344→  * `daemon start/status/abort/retry/reconcile`\n  4345→  * routing precedence\n  4346→  * task state\n  4347→  * worktree allocation\n  4348→  * task execution\n  4349→  * draft PR update\n  4350→  * rebase flow\n  4351→  * interactive requirements\n  4352→\n  4353→* **Out-of-scope**\n  4354→\n  4355→  * service extraction\n  4356→\n  4357→* **Files/modules likely affected**\n  4358→\n  4359→  * `contexts/automation_runtime/*`\n  4360→  * `adapters/github/*`\n  4361→  * `adapters/git/*`\n  4362→  * CLI daemon commands\n  4363→\n  4364→* **Ports/contracts introduced or changed**\n  4365→\n  4366→  * `GitHubPort`\n  4367→  * `WorktreePort`\n  4368→  * `TaskProcessPort`\n  4369→  * `WorkflowPort`\n  4370→  * `RequirementsPort`\n  4371→\n  4372→* **Scenarios covered**\n  4373→\n  4374→  * command-over-label routing\n  4375→  * label-only routing\n  4376→  * task abort/retry\n  4377→  * draft PR behavior\n  4378→  * rebase\n  4379→  * interactive requirements\n  4380→\n  4381→* **Test strategy**\n  4382→\n  4383→  * fake-port lifecycle tests\n  4384→  * integration with temp repos and mock GitHub\n  4385→  * conformance scenarios\n  4386→\n  4387→* **Migration strategy**\n  4388→\n  4389→  * none; new daemon only\n  4390→\n  4391→* **Rollback or safety considerations**\n  4392→\n  4393→  * terminal task state must persist before cleanup\n  4394→\n  4395→* **Risks**\n  4396→\n  4397→  * highest integration complexity in the rewrite\n  4398→\n  4399→## Slice 12: Cutover, documentation, and cleanup\n  4400→\n  4401→* **Slice name**\n  4402→  Cutover and cleanup\n  4403→\n  4404→* **Bounded context**\n  4405→  All\n  4406→\n  4407→* **Why it exists**\n  4408→  The repo should not keep two architectures indefinitely.\n  4409→\n  4410→* **Goal**\n  4411→\n  4412→  * switch the binary fully to the new runtime\n  4413→  * remove legacy orchestrator code\n  4414→  * make conformance mandatory in CI\n  4415→  * publish final architecture docs and context packs\n  4416→\n  4417→* **Prerequisites**\n  4418→\n  4419→  * Slices 1-11\n  4420→\n  4421→* **Exact scope**\n  4422→\n  4423→  * final command router cutover\n  4424→  * docs refresh\n  4425→  * CI conformance gating\n  4426→  * removal of old `src/workflow/*` orchestrator-heavy paths and reconstruction-heavy state logic\n  4427→\n  4428→* **Out-of-scope**\n  4429→\n  4430→  * legacy workspace compatibility\n  4431→\n  4432→* **Files/modules likely affected**\n  4433→\n  4434→  * command routing\n  4435→  * docs\n  4436→  * CI config\n  4437→  * old orchestration modules\n  4438→\n  4439→* **Ports/contracts introduced or changed**\n  4440→\n  4441→  * none major\n  4442→\n  4443→* **Scenarios covered**\n  4444→\n  4445→  * full supported behavior matrix\n  4446→\n  4447→* **Test strategy**\n  4448→\n  4449→  * full conformance suite\n  4450→  * adapter contract suite\n  4451→  * integration suite\n  4452→\n  4453→* **Migration strategy**\n  4454→\n  4455→  * code cutover only\n  4456→  * existing old workspaces unsupported\n  4457→\n  4458→* **Rollback or safety considerations**\n  4459→\n  4460→  * maintain the old runtime as a separate release branch if needed, not mixed into the new architecture\n  4461→\n  4462→* **Risks**\n  4463→\n  4464→  * long-lived dual architecture if cleanup is deferred\n  4465→\n  4466→# Parallelization Strategy for Multiple Agents\n  4467→\n  4468→## Which slices can run concurrently\n  4469→\n  4470→After Slice 1 stabilizes public vocabulary:\n  4471→\n  4472→* Slice 2 (workflow primitives) and Slice 3 (workspace) can proceed in parallel.\n  4473→* Slice 4 (project/run store) can proceed in parallel with Slice 5 (agent execution) once shared IDs/contracts are stable.\n  4474→* Requirements Drafting can begin once Workspace Governance and Agent Execution ports exist.\n  4475→* Conformance harness work can continue in parallel throughout.\n  4476→\n  4477→After Slices 2-5:\n  4478→\n  4479→* one agent can take the standard-flow vertical slice\n  4480→* one can implement artifact renderers and stage contract schemas\n  4481→* one can implement project query/read models and rollback infrastructure\n  4482→* one can implement validation profile adapters\n  4483→\n  4484→After Slice 7:\n  4485→\n  4486→* one agent can work on completion/final review\n  4487→* one can implement quick_dev/docs/CI presets\n  4488→* one can implement requirements drafting\n  4489→\n  4490→Automation Runtime should start only after workflow and requirements ports are stable.\n  4491→\n  4492→## Handoff boundaries\n  4493→\n  4494→Use contracts, not folders, as handoff boundaries:\n  4495→\n  4496→* `FlowDefinition`\n  4497→* `StageDefinition`\n  4498→* `StageContract`\n  4499→* `RunSnapshot`\n  4500→* `StagePayloadEnvelope`\n  4501→* `BackendSpec`\n  4502→* `InvocationResult`\n  4503→* `EffectiveConfig`\n  4504→* `RequirementsRunState`\n  4505→* `TaskRecord`\n  4506→\n  4507→## Contract-first coordination points\n  4508→\n  4509→Stabilize these before broad parallel work:\n  4510→\n  4511→* shared IDs and enums\n  4512→* stage contract conventions\n  4513→* flow preset registry shape\n  4514→* canonical run state shape\n  4515→* runtime log vs history artifact model\n  4516→* CLI vocabulary and scenario ids\n  4517→\n  4518→## Merge/conflict risks\n  4519→\n  4520→Highest-risk shared areas:\n  4521→\n  4522→* shared DTOs\n  4523→* flow catalog\n  4524→* stage contract registry\n  4525→* command router\n  4526→* conformance fixture helpers\n  4527→\n  4528→Mitigations:\n  4529→\n  4530→* one owner for shared contracts\n  4531→* one owner for command routing\n  4532→* one owner for fixture DSL\n  4533→* contract changes merged before downstream implementation branches\n  4534→\n  4535→## What should be stabilized before parallel work starts\n  4536→\n  4537→* product rename to `ralph-burning`\n  4538→* workspace root `.ralph-burning`\n  4539→* CLI surface\n  4540→* flow preset list\n  4541→* immutable flow-per-project rule\n  4542→* structured payload rule\n  4543→* log/history separation rule\n  4544→\n  4545→## How to avoid context contamination\n  4546→\n  4547→* give each agent only:\n  4548→\n  4549→  * its context pack\n  4550→  * public contracts\n  4551→  * relevant Gherkin scenarios\n  4552→* forbid direct filesystem/git calls from policy layers\n  4553→* centralize adapter ownership when practical\n  4554→* do not allow ad hoc utilities to become cross-context shortcuts\n  4555→\n  4556→## How to keep prompts/context packs compact and local\n  4557→\n  4558→* store context packs under `docs/rewrite/context-packs/`\n  4559→* each slice should reference one or two context packs maximum\n  4560→* each coding prompt should link to scenario ids rather than restating the whole architecture\n  4561→* do not hand coding agents the old repo wholesale unless they are extracting behavior references\n  4562→\n  4563→# Risks and Tradeoffs\n  4564→\n  4565→* **Where DDD helps**\n  4566→  Strongly in Workflow Composition, Project & Run Record, Requirements Drafting, and Automation Runtime because these contain real policy, language, and invariants.\n  4567→\n  4568→* **Where DDD would be overkill**\n  4569→  In CLI parsing, tiny render helpers, simple config serialization, and thin transport wrappers.\n  4570→\n  4571→* **Where hexagonal architecture helps**\n  4572→  Around workflow policy, project state, backend execution, requirements flows, and daemon routing because these must be insulated from filesystem, git, GitHub, and subprocess concerns.\n  4573→\n  4574→* **Where ports/adapters would add unnecessary indirection**\n  4575→  For pure renderers, small DTO mappers, tiny formatters, and static schema modules.\n  4576→\n  4577→* **Major abstraction risk**\n  4578→  Building a workflow language instead of a workflow engine. V1 should use typed built-in presets, not arbitrary user-authored flow DSLs.\n  4579→\n  4580→* **Structured output tradeoff**\n  4581→  Structured payloads remove syntax/reformat fragility, but they do not eliminate semantic validation. The system still needs domain-level checks.\n  4582→\n  4583→* **Markdown tradeoff**\n  4584→  Keeping markdown artifacts is useful for humans, but only if they remain derived outputs and never become the source of truth again.\n  4585→\n  4586→* **Greenfield storage tradeoff**\n  4587→  Dropping compatibility makes the architecture cleaner and safer, but it means no in-place upgrade path for legacy workspaces.\n  4588→\n  4589→* **Flow immutability tradeoff**\n  4590→  Fixing a flow preset per project reduces flexibility, but it sharply simplifies run-state correctness and operator expectations.\n  4591→\n  4592→* **Final review tradeoff**\n  4593→  Preset-specific final review prevents meaningless ritual on low-risk flows, but it requires thoughtful defaults and clear operator visibility.\n  4594→\n  4595→* **CLI modernization tradeoff**\n  4596→  A cleaner CLI improves usability, but it requires explicit documentation because old command muscle memory no longer applies.\n  4597→\n  4598→# Assumptions\n  4599→\n  4600→* The rewrite product name is `ralph-burning`.\n  4601→* The new workspace root is `.ralph-burning/`.\n  4602→* The rewrite is greenfield in storage and artifact format.\n  4603→* The old repository is used for behavior/domain reference only.\n  4604→* Legacy `.ralph` state and artifact compatibility is out of scope.\n  4605→* Rust remains the implementation language.\n  4606→* The target deployment model is a modular monolith.\n  4607→* Flow preset is fixed per project for v1.\n  4608→* The only built-in flow presets in v1 are:\n  4609→\n  4610→  * `standard`\n  4611→  * `quick_dev`\n  4612→  * `docs_change`\n  4613→  * `ci_improvement`\n  4614→* All supported backends must return structured stage payloads.\n  4615→* Human-readable markdown artifacts remain desirable and durable.\n  4616→* Runtime logs remain important but are not part of durable project history.\n  4617→* `flow list` and `flow show` are part of the public CLI.\n  4618→* Daemon routing uses both labels and explicit commands, with commands taking precedence.\n  4619→* Final review is preset-specific rather than universal.\n  4620→* The suggested validation defaults in this spec are acceptable unless explicitly revised during detailed design.\n  4621→\n  4622→# Open Questions\n  4623→\n  4624→* Should the CLI expose `cycle` terminology everywhere, or keep a compatibility-facing `loop` alias purely as user vocabulary?\n  4625→* Should `run tail` show only durable history by default, with `--logs` opt-in, or should it show a mixed recent activity stream?\n  4626→* Should `quick_dev` use a single lightweight final reviewer by default, or a very small review panel?\n  4627→* How should repo-specific validation targets be discovered:\n  4628→\n  4629→  * explicit project config\n  4630→  * conventional script names\n  4631→  * auto-detection with override\n  4632→* Should `requirements` support a convenience command that directly creates and starts a project, or should the v1 surface keep those steps explicit?\n  4633→* What should the exact default label vocabulary be if `ralph-burning` must coexist with other bots on the same repository?\n  4634→* How much raw backend output should be retained by default before runtime log cleanup?\n  4635→* Should the workspace include a first-class `backend list` / `backend check` CLI in v1, or is backend validation during run start sufficient?\n  4636→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01TEaD8r9ay6pGSRWy6ah8ZA","session_id":"62aed473-a912-4db2-a48b-52d5c598eaf3","uuid":"06e5852c-1314-470a-8906-e2a2dafbf58a"}
